orial Prize in Economic Sciences<\/a> in 1992 and received the United States <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Presidential_Medal_of_Freedom\" title=\"Presidential Medal of Freedom\">Presidential Medal of Freedom<\/a> in 2007.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gary_S._Becker#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was a Rose-Marie and Jack R. Anderson senior fellow at the conservative<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gary_S._Becker#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hoover_Institution\" title=\"Hoover Institution\">Hoover Institution<\/a>, located at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stanford_University\" title=\"Stanford University\">Stanford University<\/a>.<\/p><p>Becker was one of the first economists to branch into what were traditionally considered topics belonging to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sociology\" title=\"Sociology\">sociology<\/a>, including <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Racial_discrimination\" title=\"Racial discrimination\" class=\"mw-redirect\">racial discrimination<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Crime\" title=\"Crime\">crime<\/a>, family organization, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Drug_addiction\" title=\"Drug addiction\" class=\"mw-redirect\">drug addiction<\/a> (see <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rational_addiction\" title=\"Rational addiction\">rational addiction<\/a>). He was known for arguing that many different types of human behavior can be seen as rational and utility maximizing. His approach included <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Altruistic_behavior\" title=\"Altruistic behavior\" class=\"mw-redirect\">altruistic behavior<\/a> of human behavior by defining individuals' utility appropriately. He was also among the foremost exponents of the study of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Human_capital\" title=\"Human capital\">human capital<\/a>. Becker was also credited with the \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rotten_kid_theorem\" title=\"Rotten kid theorem\">rotten kid theorem<\/a>.\"<\/p>","name":"Gary S. Becker","place_of_birth":"Pottsville, Pennsylvania , U.S.","place_of_death":"Chicago, Illinois, U.S.","text":"Gary S. Becker , Economics, 1992","year":1992.0}